# DIGITAL LITERACY PORTFOLIO PROJECT REPORT

**Course Code:** CSE0001
**Course Title:** Digital Literacy
**Student Name:** Aditya Yadav
**Program:** B.Tech – First Year
**Institution:** VIT Bhopal University

---

# Introduction

Digital literacy is an essential skill in today’s world where almost every academic, professional, and personal activity depends on digital platforms. As a first-year engineering student, it is important to understand how to use digital tools responsibly, communicate professionally online, and stay safe from cyber threats. This project was designed to help students develop these important skills through practical tasks and real-world applications.

The Digital Literacy Portfolio consists of five different tasks, each focusing on a different aspect of digital awareness. These tasks include creating a digital literacy infographic, building a professional online portfolio, exploring coding and collaboration platforms, writing professional emails, and studying cybercrime awareness. Through this project, I learned not only how to use digital platforms but also how to present myself professionally and responsibly in the digital world.

---

# Task 1 – Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic

For this task, I created a digital literacy awareness infographic using an online design tool. The main objective of the infographic was to explain the meaning of digital literacy and why it is important for students. The infographic included topics such as safe internet practices, useful digital tools for students, and the importance of maintaining a professional online presence.

While designing the infographic, I focused on making it simple, attractive, and easy to understand. I used clear headings, short points, and visually appealing elements to make the information more effective. The design highlights how students can use digital platforms in a safe and responsible way while also improving their academic performance.

One thing I found interesting while working on this task was how visual communication can make information easier to understand compared to plain text. At the same time, choosing the right design and organizing the content properly was a bit challenging. However, this task helped me improve my creativity and understand the importance of presenting information in a professional way.

---

# Task 2 – Student Digital Portfolio

In this task, I created and updated my digital profiles on professional platforms such as GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle. The main goal of this task was to build a professional online identity that can help in future academic and career opportunities.

GitHub is mainly used for sharing coding projects and technical work. Creating a GitHub profile helped me understand how developers share their work and collaborate with others. LinkedIn is a professional networking platform where students and professionals can connect with companies, recruiters, and other learners. Updating my LinkedIn profile helped me understand the importance of maintaining a professional image online. Kaggle is a platform used for data science and machine learning practice. Creating a Kaggle profile helped me explore new learning opportunities in the field of technology.

This task helped me realize that building a professional digital presence should start from the first year of college. Over the next four years, I plan to regularly update my profiles, upload projects, and improve my technical skills. This will help me prepare for internships and future job opportunities.

---

# Task 3 – Coding & Collaboration Platforms

The objective of this task was to explore coding practice platforms and collaboration tools that can help students improve their academic performance. For the coding practice part, I created an account on a coding platform and completed a beginner-level challenge. This helped me understand how coding platforms work and how they can be used to improve programming skills through practice.

For the collaboration part, I created a Google Form titled “Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz.” The form includes five questions related to digital literacy and online safety. This task helped me learn how to create online forms and collect responses using Google Sheets. It also showed how digital tools can be used to conduct quizzes, surveys, and academic activities easily.

This task was very useful because it introduced me to tools that I can use throughout my engineering studies. Coding practice platforms will help me improve my programming skills, and Google Forms will help me in academic projects and group work.

---

# Task 4 – Professional Email & Social Media Etiquette

In this task, I learned how to write professional emails and how to communicate properly in an academic or professional environment. I wrote two professional emails: one requesting an assignment extension from a professor and another expressing interest in a summer internship opportunity. While writing these emails, I focused on using a clear subject line, a respectful greeting, a well-structured body, and a proper sign-off.

In addition to the emails, I also created a Social Media Do’s and Don’ts checklist. This checklist explains how students should behave responsibly on social media platforms. Social media is a very important part of student life, but it must be used carefully. Posting inappropriate content or sharing personal information can create serious problems in the future.

One important lesson I learned from this task is that digital communication should always be professional and respectful. A simple mistake in an email or social media post can create a negative impression. Therefore, students should always think before sending messages or posting content online.

---

# Task 5 – Cybercrime Awareness Case Study

The objective of this task was to understand cybercrime and how students can protect themselves from online threats. For this task, I wrote a case study on phishing. Phishing is a type of cybercrime in which attackers try to steal personal information by pretending to be a trusted organization or person.

While researching this topic, I learned that students are one of the most common targets of phishing attacks because they use the internet frequently and may not always verify emails or links. Cybercriminals often send fake emails that look real and ask users to enter their passwords or personal details. Once the information is shared, it can be misused in many ways.

I also created a “Stay Safe Online” checklist that includes practical safety tips for college students in India. The checklist includes tips related to password safety, avoiding suspicious links, protecting personal information, and safe use of UPI and online payments. This task helped me understand the importance of cyber awareness and how small precautions can prevent major problems.

---

# What Surprised Me the Most

While working on this project, the thing that surprised me the most was how common cybercrime has become. Even simple mistakes like clicking on an unknown link or sharing an OTP can lead to serious problems. I also realized that many students are not aware of basic online safety rules.

As a result of this project, one habit I will personally change is being more careful while using the internet. I will always check links before clicking, avoid sharing personal information online, and use strong passwords for all my accounts.

---

# Conclusion

This Digital Literacy Portfolio project was very helpful in improving my understanding of digital platforms and online safety. It helped me learn how to create a professional digital presence, use online tools for academic purposes, write professional emails, and stay safe from cybercrime.

Through this project, I also understood that digital literacy is not only about using technology but also about using it responsibly and professionally. The knowledge gained from this project will help me throughout my engineering studies and in my future career.

